  "context_summary": "2-year-old girl brought in by her mother for foul-smelling discharge from her right nostril, noticed today, with no clear story of what happened. The child is too young to reliably describe what occurred. The doctor has not yet visualized the nasal cavity and is deciding between routine outpatient removal versus urgent same-visit or ED-level intervention, which depends heavily on what the object might be and how long it's been there.",
  "good_next_question": "When was the last time you saw her playing with any small toys, beads, button batteries, or food like beans or nuts near her nose, and about how long ago do you think that might have been?",
  "rationale": "In pediatric foreign body cases, history from the child is unreliable, so the caregiver's recollection of exposure and rough timeline is the primary diagnostic tool available before direct visualization. Establishing how long the object has likely been in place matters because prolonged retention, especially of button batteries or organic material like beans or nuts, increases the risk of tissue necrosis, infection, or septal perforation, which changes this from a routine outpatient removal to an emergent ENT or ED intervention. Identifying what objects were accessible also narrows the type of foreign body: a button battery requires emergent removal within hours due to caustic injury risk, while a bead or foam piece is time-sensitive but far less urgent. This is more useful than asking about symptoms alone, since a toddler can't reliably localize or describe symptoms, while a witnessed or inferred exposure timeline gives an actionable data point for triage urgency.",
  "tags": [
    "ent",
    "foreign_body",
    "peds",
    "pediatric",
    "nasal_foreign_body",
    "toddler"
  ],
